    <!-- TWO PANS, TWO BUSINESSES, ZERO OVERLAP -->
    <section class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-12 border-b border-ink/10">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl text-ink mb-2">Variolearn — son's separate sole prop under his own PAN</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink/60 mb-6">MGS lives entirely under mom's PAN. Variolearn (the son's IT side project) lives entirely under his own PAN. Two separate legal persons, two separate sole prop trade names, zero overlap. This is the cleanest possible structure.</p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-ink mt-2 mb-3">Why two PANs, not one</h3>
      <p class="su-body" style="font-size: 14px; color: rgba(42,26,16,0.8); line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 16px;">
        Earlier draft of this plan considered running both under the son's PAN. Final decision: <strong>MGS goes in mom's name</strong>. Reasons:
      </p>
      <ul class="su-bullets">
        <li><strong>Employer visibility for the son drops to zero on the food business.</strong> The IT employer cannot find MGS by searching the son's PAN on the GST portal. Anti-moonlighting policies don't apply because the food business legally isn't his.</li>
        <li><strong>Tax efficiency.</strong> Mom's slab is lower than the son's IT-salary slab → less total household tax.</li>
        <li><strong>Honest paperwork.</strong> Mom cooks, mom's home = the kitchen, mom's name on the FSSAI license. The license address matches reality.</li>
        <li><strong>Mom owns the brand asset permanently.</strong> If the son ever leaves the IT job, gets married, moves cities, or pivots to Variolearn full-time — MGS continues under mom uninterrupted.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-ink mt-8 mb-3">Side-by-side: MGS (mom's) vs Variolearn (son's)</h3>
      <div class="su-table-wrap">
        <table class="su-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Item</th><th>Mother's Gold Spice</th><th>Variolearn</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Legal entity</td><td>Mom — Sole Proprietorship</td><td>Son — Sole Proprietorship</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PAN used</td><td>Mom's</td><td>Son's</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Aadhaar used</td><td>Mom's</td><td>Son's</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GSTIN</td><td>One in mom's PAN (Karnataka)</td><td>Separate one in son's PAN (Karnataka)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Udyam (MSME)</td><td>In mom's name, listed as "Pickle manufacturing"</td><td>In son's name, listed as "Software / Edtech services"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shops & Establishments</td><td>In mom's name at her home</td><td>In son's name at his rental flat</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Bank current account</td><td>In mom's name, "a/c Mother's Gold Spice"</td><td>In son's name, "a/c Variolearn"</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Trademark</td><td>Class 29 (pickles), filed by mom</td><td>Class 9 (software) or 41 (edtech), filed by son</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Razorpay account</td><td>Mom's — linked to her bank</td><td>Son's — linked to his bank</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Domain + website</td><td>mothersgoldspice.com (owned by mom)</td><td>variolearn.com (owned by son)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>FSSAI</td><td>Required, in mom's name, at her home</td><td>Not required (software)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shiprocket</td><td>Required, mom's KYC, picks up at her home</td><td>Not required (digital product)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ITR (income tax)</td><td>Mom files her own (ITR-3 or 4)</td><td>Son files his own (ITR-3 with salary + business)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="su-outcome">Outcome: <strong>Zero overlap.</strong> Mom is the legal owner + tax payer of MGS. Son is the legal owner + tax payer of Variolearn. They share an operational rhythm (mom cooks, son ships) but the businesses are legally completely independent.</div>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-ink mt-10 mb-3">Son's role in MGS — operational helper, not partner</h3>
      <p class="su-body" style="font-size: 14px; color: rgba(42,26,16,0.78); line-height: 1.65;">
        For MGS, the son acts as mom's <strong>authorized representative / signatory on the bank account</strong>, but is NOT a co-proprietor or partner. This distinction matters:
      </p>
      <ul class="su-bullets">
        <li>Son can <strong>operate</strong> the website, Razorpay, Shiprocket, customer service, packing, shipping</li>
        <li>Son can <strong>sign cheques</strong> and transfer money from mom's business account (as authorized signatory)</li>
        <li>Son's PAN is <strong>NOT on any MGS registration</strong> — no GST, no FSSAI, no Udyam, no trademark</li>
        <li>Mom is the <strong>only legal entity</strong> behind MGS</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="su-body" style="font-size: 14px; color: rgba(42,26,16,0.78); line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 12px;">
        This is the same structure as a one-person family-owned shop where one family member legally owns the shop and others help run it. Common, simple, completely legal.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-ink mt-10 mb-3">Cost of setting up Variolearn separately</h3>
      <p class="su-body" style="font-size: 14px; color: rgba(42,26,16,0.78); line-height: 1.65; margin-bottom: 12px;">
        Variolearn's setup is a separate exercise — its own Sole Prop, its own GST, its own bank account, all in the son's PAN. Roughly mirrors MGS's setup steps but without FSSAI or Shiprocket.
      </p>
      <div class="su-table-wrap">
        <table class="su-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Cost</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Udyam (in son's name)</td><td>₹0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shops & Establishments at son's flat</td><td>₹250–1,000</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Business current account (son's)</td><td>₹0 fee</td></tr>
            <tr><td>GST registration (son's PAN)</td><td>₹0</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Trademark (Class 9 or 41, MSME rate)</td><td>₹4,500</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Domain (variolearn.com via Cloudflare)</td><td>~₹1,000/year</td></tr>
            <tr class="su-table-total"><td><strong>Total for Variolearn</strong></td><td><strong>~₹5,750–6,500</strong></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="su-body" style="font-size: 14px; color: rgba(42,26,16,0.78); line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 12px;">
        <strong>Two completely separate setups, each ~₹6–8k</strong>. Compare to keeping both under one PAN (would have been ~₹13–15k total but with the visibility risk). The two-PAN structure is similar cost, much cleaner separation.
